abstract = {This essay is an attempt to understand the role of connectivity, mobility, and public transportation in our neighborhoods within the context of urban development and the future of sustainable cities. When viewed from both, the design and planning standpoint, as well as financial perspective, it reinforces the importance of transit-oriented development in urban environments. This is realized through the analysis of two “smart cases”—one is a proposed Smart Central Business District in Wadala, Mumbai, and the other is part of the 100 Smart Cities supported by the Smart Cities Mission of the Government of India currently being implemented in Bengaluru. Connectivity, mobility, and public transportation are crucial to both these urban developments. Through these two examples this essay reinforces that effective long-term value of mobility and transportation is better realized when they are not viewed as isolated entities. Mobility and transport's value is better captured when placed within the larger ecosystem of Urbanization and Urban Planning. It is imperative that all developments address comprehensive master planning of cities and go beyond the innovative technologies that provide smart infrastructure. This may be accomplished by inclusive design, integrating land use, and transport planning, emphasizing on best practices that minimize a city's carbon footprint and providing services such as energy efficiency, equitable transport, opportunities for livelihood improvement, etc. Only then can true long-term value be realized and our cities achieve ecological sustainability and socioeconomic equilibrium.}
